  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Rightness -- the experiment doesn't need moral overload at every term",
    "content": "**Rightness.**\n\nThe philosophical experiment argument cuts both ways. Yes, the reader needs semantic weight to feel the reversal. But if *every* term is maximally loaded -- the Way, virtue, humaneness, *righteousness*, ritual conduct -- the passage becomes so morally heavy that the reader cannot see past the moral frame to follow the structural argument. The experiment is about the *structure of abstraction* (how bottom-up phenomenological observation gets inverted into top-down metaphysical hierarchy), not about morality specifically. If the English is saturated with moral-religious language, the reader will experience the reversal as \"morality is a social construction\" rather than \"metaphysical hierarchies are inversions of phenomenological genesis.\" That is a misreading.\n\nThe 德 split already carries the moral-to-structural deconstructive weight (virtue -> character). We do not need义 to do the same work. \"Rightness\" gives the reader enough to feel -- it activates a sense of correctness, appropriateness, what-should-be-done -- without the biblical/religious overtones of \"righteousness\" that would pull the reader into a morality debate the author is not having.\n\nAlso: the author defines 义 as 推动力, a motivational force -- \"what my feeling impels me to do.\" \"Rightness\" fits this better than \"righteousness.\" You feel a sense of *rightness* about an action and it moves you; you do not feel \"righteousness\" as an impulse -- in English, righteousness is a *judgment*, not a *motivation*."
  }
}
